      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 used under ISO 9001-certified QMS; version-controlled input decks archived in FDA CDRH internal repository.",
      "rationale": "Commercial solver (Ansys Mechanical) operates under vendor-maintained QMS with documented release verification. Internal version control confirmed for all simulation input files. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems (NAFEMS LE1, LE10) reproduced within 1% of analytical solutions; patch test passed for all element types employed.",
      "rationale": "Standard NAFEMS benchmarks verified correct implementation of linear and nonlinear solid elements. Patch test confirmed element completeness. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study performed across three refinement levels; QoI change <2% between finest two meshes.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study conducted on screw shank and rod-screw interface regions. Stiffness QoI changed by 1.3% between medium and fine meshes; yield force by 0.9%. Richardson extrapolation confirmed GCI < 1.5% for all reported QoIs. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson residual convergence tolerance 1e-4; energy criterion 1e-6; no divergence events across all 11 model instances.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static solver converged for all load steps across all 11 construct replicate models. Residual force norms and energy norms met specified tolerances. No hourglassing observed in reduced-integration elements. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation protocol reviewed by independent analyst; boundary condition application and material assignment verified by second engineer.",
      "rationale": "Independent peer review of simulation setup performed by a second FDA engineer not involved in original model construction. Boundary conditions, contact definitions, and material assignments confirmed correct. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with elastic-plastic Ti-6Al-4V material law; contact interfaces at screw-rod and screw-vertebral body block; large-deformation kinematics enabled.",
      "rationale": "Isotropic elastic-plastic material model with bilinear hardening calibrated from Ti-6Al-4V coupon data. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at rod-screw interface captures load transfer mechanism. Large-deformation formulation active for post-yield regime. Physics representation appropriate for quasi-static compression-bending. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties derived from certified coupon test data (n=5 per lot); geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of as-tested constructs.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus, yield strength, and tangent modulus sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon testing (n=5). Screw outer diameter, thread pitch, and rod diameter verified by coordinate measuring machine on representative samples. Input uncertainty propagated via ±1 standard deviation sensitivity study; QoI variation <4%. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs from production lots; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to drawing tolerances; no outliers excluded without documented justification.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs sourced from two production lots and tested across two laboratories. Dimensional inspection confirmed all screws within ±0.05 mm of nominal. No constructs excluded from analysis. Sample size provides adequate statistical power for mean QoI comparison. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions should span at least two loading rates and two fixation torque levels to characterize sensitivity of QoIs to test setup variability.",
      "rationale": "All experimental testing was conducted at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min) and a single screw insertion torque (8 Nm) per ASTM F1717 protocol. While the standard prescribes these nominal conditions and inter-laboratory reproducibility was confirmed, no parametric variation of loading rate or fixation torque was performed. The team notes that ASTM F1717 is a standardized protocol and deviations from its prescribed conditions are not typical in regulatory submissions. Overall model agreement is strong across all other factors, supporting the Accepted decision."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and material inputs traceable to as-tested experimental conditions; documented mapping between test setup and model setup.",
      "rationale": "Displacement-controlled boundary condition in FEA mirrors experimental crosshead control. Screw insertion torque converted to preload via thread mechanics model and applied as initial contact pressure. Material properties from same production lot as tested constructs. Formal input equivalency table prepared and reviewed. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs; percent difference <10% for mean stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement.",
      "rationale": "For all three QoIs: stiffness error 4.2% (E/uval=0.87), yield force error 3.8% (E/uval=0.74), force at 40 mm error 6.1% (E/uval=1.21). All values within pre-established acceptance bounds. Validation metric computed per ASME V&V 40 Eq. 3.1 incorporating experimental uncertainty from both laboratories. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) directly correspond to regulatory submission endpoints and failure mode indicators for pedicle screw fatigue and fracture risk.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing between implant and bone graft. Yield force and force at 40 mm displacement are standard ASTM F1717 regulatory endpoints used to characterize fatigue and fracture resistance. All three QoIs are directly relevant to the COU decision. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity geometry, material, loading mode, and boundary conditions match COU within documented similarity bounds.",
      "rationale": "Validation constructs use identical screw geometry, material lot, and ASTM F1717 test fixture as the COU submission. Loading mode (compression-bending) and displacement range match intended regulatory use. No extrapolation beyond validated geometry or loading envelope is claimed. Required level 3 achieved."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou1-noncannulated-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-fda-cdrh-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The FEA modeling framework for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct under ASTM F1717 compression-bending has demonstrated adequate credibility for the intended regulatory submission. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. Quantitative validation metrics (E/uval < 1.96, percent error < 10%) are satisfied for all three QoIs across N=11 constructs from two independent laboratories, providing strong evidence of model fidelity. The Test conditions factor reflects a standard regulatory testing protocol conducted at a single prescribed loading rate and torque; the assessment team considers this consistent with industry practice for ASTM F1717 submissions and notes that the strong inter-laboratory agreement corroborates experimental reproducibility. On balance, the totality of evidence supports acceptance of the simulation results for the stated context of use.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
